<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="85" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="85">
The phylogeny results showed that the CGMCC 3.20955, GZUIFR 22.037 and GZUIFR 22.038 still nested in the 
<taxonomicName genus="Pinkertoniae" lsidName="Pinkertoniae" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Pinkertoniae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-clade. The morphological characteristics of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Xin Li, Y. F. Han &amp; Z. Q. Liang" authorityYear="2022" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Bionectriaceae" genus="Acremonium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Acremonium globosisporum" order="Hypocreales" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="globosisporum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Acremonium globosisporum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were similar to other species of the 
<taxonomicName genus="Pinkertoniae" lsidName="Pinkertoniae" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Pinkertoniae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-clade in that phialides were erect on the hyphae; sporulation was abundant, and conidia were subglobose (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1017/S0953756299008977" author="Ito, T" journalOrPublisher="Mycological Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" pagination="77 - 80" refId="B6" refString="Ito, T, Okane, I, Nakagiri, A, Gams, W, 2000. Two species of Acremonium section Acremonium: A. borodinense sp. nov. and A. cavaraeanum rediscovered. Mycological Research 104 (1): 77 - 80, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1017/S0953756299008977" title="Two species of Acremonium section Acremonium: A. borodinense sp. nov. and A. cavaraeanum rediscovered." url="https://doi.org/10.1017/S0953756299008977" volume="104" year="2000">Ito et al. 2000</bibRefCitation>
). However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Xin Li, Y. F. Han &amp; Z. Q. Liang" authorityYear="2022" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Bionectriaceae" genus="Acremonium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Acremonium globosisporum" order="Hypocreales" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="globosisporum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Acremonium globosisporum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
hyphae were sometimes winding and inflated, with conidia cohering in long chains, unlike other species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
